Lesson Summary
What is Local Government?
What is local government? The definition of local government is the government of a town, city, or county. Towns, cities, and countries exist as divisions within a state. In other words, local government is subordinate to both the state and federal governments.
Different states have varying laws that deal with how local governments are formed, as well as how they function. For instance, some states give a great deal of authority to counties, while others provide countries with almost no real political power.
Local governments are the governments that ordinary people have the most direct control over. This is due to the fact that communities have much smaller populations than states or countries.
City Hall in Elizabethtown, NJ
What Does the Local Government Do?
Local governments are responsible for the day-to-day activities of the community. Here are some common local government responsibilities:
Running the police department
Running the local schools
Running the trash collection service
Running the fire department
Issuing and collecting property taxes
Animal control
Passing ordinances (local laws)
Plowing snow
Maintaining roads (responsibility often shared with the state government)
Zoning property
Issuing certain types of licenses and permits
Maintaining parks, beaches, and other public spaces
Running municipal utilities
Running libraries
How Does Local Government Work?
How does local government work? Cities, towns, and counties work in different ways in different states. However, generally speaking, local governments receive most of their funding via property taxes. This is a tax levied against property owned by a person or business. (It is important to note, however, that tax assessors do not work for local governments. State taxes are the responsibility of state governments.)
Local Government Structure
Almost all local governments are led by elected officials who act in a similar way as governors, congressmen, and presidents. On rare occasions, a state government may take over the government of a city or town when there is widespread corruption, bankruptcy, natural disasters, or other similar circumstances. In these cases, local control is eventually handed over back to the city or town. The specific structure of a local government varies, depending of the laws of the state. Usually, however, most local governments contain an executive branch, legislative branch, and judicial branch.
Local Government and State Government
All local governments must abide by the laws of their states. Just as U.S. states can not violate federal law, municipal governments are not allowed to partake in activities that violate the laws of the states in which they exist. For instance, the mayor of New York City can not appoint the district attorney of Manhattan. This can only be done by the voters of the borough of Manhattan or the governor of the state (when there is a vacancy).
Most states offer funding and other types of support to local communities. This involves funding for education, public services, the police, et cetera.
Local Government and Federal Government
Local governments must also abide by the U.S. Constitution and federal law. While this may seem like common sense, there have been many instances in U.S. history when local governments have undertaken actions that violate federal law. For instance, many local communities have tried to ban certain books. Federal courts have ruled that these actions violate the First Amendment of the Constitution.
Local governments may receive funding and assistance from the federal government. For instance, after 9/11, many local police departments received anti-terrorist training and supplies from Washington.
